html.body: CYCLIN E module At the end of G1 phase, Cyclin E1 binds to CDK2 to form an active complex. Its activity is shut off by the formation of inactive trimers with the cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitors p27KIP1 and p21CIP1 (PMID:10385618). As cyclin E1 is synthesized, more complexes become active and CycE1/CDK2 is capable of phosphorylating p130 and p107 to release and inactivate E2F4 repressing transcriptional activity (PMID:11237530) but also RB to complete its inactivation started by CycD1/CDK4,6 (PMID:9315635). E2F1 is than released from the complex, which in turn, allows the synthesis of more cyclin E1. CycE1/CDK2 is also responsible for the phosphorylation of p27KIP1 which results in targeting p27KIP1 for degradation (PMID:10385618). CycE1/CDK2 level drops abruptly towards the end of the cycle (M phase).
